              'Grade 6-7': 'Sharma constructs her argument through a rhetorical architecture that moves from the material to the moral. The opening redefinition — "Fast fashion is not fashion at all" — performs an act of linguistic repossession, stripping the word "fashion" of its glamour and replacing it with "industrialised waste." The phrase "dressed up in a crop top" operates as a multi-layered pun: "dressed up" simultaneously evokes disguise and the fashion industry itself, collapsing the distinction between product and problem. The second paragraph shifts register from statistical to narrative with the Rana Plaza reference, moving from the abstract ("350,000 tonnes") to the devastatingly specific ("1,134 people"). The verb sequence "scrolling," "clicking," "next-day deliveries" accelerates through consumer behaviour with present participles that suggest compulsive, unthinking repetition. The third paragraph\'s strategic concession — "I do not blame individuals" — redirects culpability from consumer to corporation, and the closing epigram transforms the literal "price tag" into a metaphor for moral accountability, the word "true" carrying the weight of the entire argument.',
