              'Grade 4-5': 'Gaskell uses humour and exaggeration to criticise fashion. The description of the crinoline making it impossible to "pass through a doorway without turning sideways" creates a comic image that makes the fashion seem ridiculous. The phrase "social ruin" is dramatic — being refused entry to a dinner because a dress was not wide enough seems absurd. Gaskell calls fashion "that most capricious of rulers," a metaphor that compares fashion to a tyrant, showing that women have no choice. The phrase "tyranny of it" makes fashion sound oppressive rather than enjoyable. The contrast between the cost of "one year\'s wardrobe" and clothing "a poor family for five" appeals to the reader\'s sense of injustice.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Gaskell deploys a rhetorical strategy of comic escalation that gradually transforms amusement into moral outrage. The opening concessive — "I cannot pretend to understand" — establishes an ironic pose of bewildered reasonableness, positioning the writer as the rational observer of collective madness. The physical comedy of the crinoline — women unable to pass through doorways, "propelled onto the floor" — functions as satire: the absurdity of the image indicts the fashion itself. The verb "propelled" is particularly effective, suggesting the women have become passive objects of their own clothing. The anecdote of the refused dinner guest sharpens the comedy into social critique — "as though the circumference of one\'s skirts were a measure of one\'s worth" uses the scientific language of measurement ("circumference") to expose the irrationality of social judgment. The metaphor of fashion as "that most capricious of rulers" elevates the critique from personal taste to political tyranny, the adjective "capricious" emphasising the arbitrary, unaccountable nature of fashion\'s authority. The final appeal to economic morality — contrasting one wardrobe with five years of clothing for the poor — shifts the register from satire to sermon, and the closing rhetorical balance of "vanity and virtue" uses alliteration to frame the choice as a moral binary.',
