              'Grade 4-5': 'Mill uses strong, confident language to defend the press. The opening metaphor "the cornerstone upon which all other liberties rest" makes press freedom sound essential — like a foundation stone that holds everything up. The tricolon "a noisy liberty, an inconvenient liberty, and frequently an abused liberty" admits the press is not perfect but uses the repeated word "liberty" to remind the reader what is at stake. The list of the press\'s faults — printing "scandal and rumour with equal enthusiasm" — shows that Mill is being fair and balanced, which makes his argument more convincing. The anaphoric "It was the press that..." is repeated three times to build a powerful list of the press\'s achievements. The final sentence — "Silence the press, and you silence the people" — uses repetition and a short, imperative structure to create a memorable, powerful ending.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Mill constructs his defence through a strategy of comprehensive concession: he grants every criticism of the press before demonstrating that freedom outweighs all faults. The architectural metaphor of the "cornerstone" is deliberately foundational — it positions press freedom not as one liberty among many but as the structural precondition for all others. The tricolon "noisy... inconvenient... abused" employs ascending severity while maintaining the anchor word "liberty," creating a rhetorical tension between the adjectives of criticism and the noun of principle. The second paragraph\'s catalogue of faults is rhetorically necessary — by articulating the strongest case against the press, Mill immunises his argument against rebuttal. The comparative "A murder in Whitechapel will command more column inches than a famine in India" uses geographical and moral disproportion to concede the press\'s failure of priority while implicitly arguing that the solution is better journalism, not less. The anaphoric construction "It was the press that..." in the final paragraph builds from the institutional (workhouses) through the military (Crimea) to the universal ("gave voice to the voiceless"), creating an ascending scale of moral achievement. The closing epigram — "Silence the press, and you silence the people" — deploys the imperative mood to transform the hypothetical into the consequential, the parallel structure creating an equation: press = people.',
